'''Deathnium''' is a name given by early electronic engineers to a trap in [[semiconductors]] that reduced the lifetime of both electron and hole [[charge carriers]]. It is considered the fifth of the imperfections that must be considered in semiconductor crystals to understand semiconductor effects along with [[Electron hole|holes]], [[Electron|electrons]], [[Donor (semiconductors)|donors]], and [[Acceptor (semiconductors)|acceptors]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=Nobel Lectures in Physics, Volumes 1942-1962|last=|first=|publisher=World Scientific|year=1998|isbn=9810234031|location=Singapore|pages=347}}</ref> Deathnium hastens the establishment of equilibrium between holes and electrons.<ref name=":0" /> This condition was not anticipated but it emerged during the invention of [[bipolar junction transistor]] after the influence of deep-trap impurities introduced by contamination of the manufacturing machinery, which reduced the lifetime of semiconductor.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Patents, Inventions and the Dynamics of Innovation: A Multidisciplinary Study|last=Cullis|first=Roger|publisher=Edward Elgar Publishing|year=2007|isbn=9781845429584|location=Cheltenham, UK|pages=272}}</ref>

