{{Other uses|Parthenope (disambiguation){{!}}Parthenope}} {{Infobox mythical creature |name = Parthenope |AKA = |image = Spinacorona.jpg |image_size = |caption = The [[Fountain of the Spinacorona, Naples|Fountain of the Spinacorona]], a depiction of Parthenope in [[Naples]]. |Mythology = [[Greek mythology|Greek]] |Grouping = Mythological |Sub_Grouping = [[Siren (mythology)|Siren]] |Parents = [[Achelous]] and [[Terpsichore]] |Country = [[Greece]] |Region = [[Sirenum scopuli]] |Habitat = Seagirt meadows |Similar_creatures = }} [[File:Delle imprese trattato detail.jpg|thumb|right|Illustration of Parthenope from the ''Delle imprese trattato'' by [[Giulio Cesare Capaccio]]]] '''Parthenope''' ({{lang-grc-gre|Παρθενόπη}}) was one of the [[Siren (mythology)|Sirens]] in [[Greek mythology]]. Her name means "Maiden-voiced".<ref name="Austern&Naroditskaya">{{cite book |editor1-last=Austern |editor1-first=Linda |editor2-last=Naroditskaya |editor2-first=Inna |date=2006 |title=Music of the Sirens |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5IBSGG9YegwC&pg=PT29&dq=Parthenope+siren&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Lk6vU57oM9KOqgb904BQ&ved=0CDwQ6AEwBg#v=onepage&q&f=false |location=Bloomington, Indiana |publisher=[[Indiana University Press]] |isbn=0-253-21846-2 |accessdate=28 June 2014 }}</ref>{{rp|20}}
==Myth== According to Greek legend, Parthenope was the daughter of the [[Deity|god]] [[Achelous]] and the [[Muse]] [[Terpsichore]].<ref name="Austern&Naroditskaya" />{{rp|35}}<ref name="Spink & Son">{{cite book |author=Spink & Son |date=1906 |title=The Numismatic Circular and Catalogue of Coins, Tokens, Commemorative & War Medals, Books & Cabinets, Volume 14 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5spLAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA2-PA160&dq=Parthenope+siren&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Lk6vU57oM9KOqgb904BQ&ved=0CCYQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q&f=false |location=Piccadily |publisher=Spink & Son |page=9010 |isbn= |accessdate=28 June 2014 }}</ref> She cast herself into the sea and [[Drowning|drowned]] when her songs failed to entice [[Odysseus]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Facaros |first=Dana |last2=Pauls |first2=Michael |date=2007 |title=Bay of Naples and Southern Italy |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tNwg7eWUFL4C&pg=PA21&dq=parthenope+odysseus&hl=en&sa=X&ei=VmSvU9XpOIiWyATX9YGgBQ&ved=0CCcQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q&f=false |location=Cape Town, South Africa |publisher=[[New Holland Publishers]] |page=21 |isbn=978-1-86-011349-9 |accessdate=29 June 2014 }}</ref><ref name="Miles">{{cite book |last=Miles |first=Gary B. |date=1980 |title=Virgil's Georgics: A New Interpretation |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_MMtu-t0i_QC&pg=PA293&dq=parthenope+odysseus&hl=en&sa=X&ei=zSKwU8XQDc6XqAb6woIg&ved=0CD8Q6AEwBjgK#v=onepage&q&f=false |location=Berkeley and Los Angeles |publisher=[[University of California Press]] |isbn=0-520-03789-8 |accessdate=29 June 2014 }}</ref>{{rp|293}} Her body washed ashore at [[Naples]], on the island of Megaride, where the [[Castel dell'Ovo]] is now located.<ref>{{cite book |last=Lancaster |first=Jordan |date=2005 |title=In the Shadow of Vesuvius: A Cultural History of Naples |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TnM1g0oKkN0C&pg=PA11&dq=parthenope+megaride&hl=en&sa=X&ei=DZ2xU-CgBNGTqAbK-IGAAw&ved=0CDQQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q&f=false |location=London and New York |publisher=[[I.B. Tauris]] |page=11 |isbn=1-85043-764-5 |accessdate=30 June 2014 }}</ref> When people from the city of [[Cumae]] settled there, they named their city [[History of Naples#Greek birth, Roman acquisition|Parthenope]] in her honour.<ref name="Jansen" >{{cite book |editor1-last=Jansen |editor1-first=Laura |date=2014 |title=The Roman Paratext: Frame, Texts, Readers |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iXM9AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA230&dq=Parthenope+siren&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Lk6vU57oM9KOqgb904BQ&ved=0CCwQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q&f=false |location=Cambridge UK |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |page=230 |isbn=978-1-107-02436-6 |accessdate=30 June 2014 }}</ref>
A [[Roman mythology|Roman myth]] tells a different version of the tale, in which a [[centaur]] named Vesuvius was enamored with Parthenope. Angered, [[Jupiter (god)|Jupiter]] turned the centaur into [[Mount Vesuvius|a stratovolcano]] and Parthenope into the city of [[Naples]]. Thwarted in his desire, Vesuvius' rage is manifested in the volcano's frequent violent eruptions.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ledeen |first=Michael |date=2011 |title=Virgil's Golden Egg and Other Neapolitan Miracles: an Investigation into the Sources of Creativity |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KtufeoUMNBoC&pg=PA37&dq=parthenope+odysseus&hl=en&sa=X&ei=VmSvU9XpOIiWyATX9YGgBQ&ved=0CBwQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |location=New Brunswick, New Jersey |publisher=[[Transaction Publishers]] |page=37 |isbn=978-1-4128-4240-2 |accessdate=30 June 2014 }}</ref>
==In literature and art== Parthenope has been depicted in various forms of literature and art, from ancient coins that bore her semblance<ref name="Spink & Son" /> to the [[Fountain of the Spinacorona, Naples|Fountain of the Spinacorona]], where she is depicted quenching the fires of Vesuvius with water from her breasts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.corpodinapoli.it/ospitalita/monumenti/fontana-spinacorona.html |title=Fontana di Spinacorona (detta Fontana delle zizze) |website=CorpodiNapoli |accessdate=30 June 2014 }}</ref> In his ''[[Georgics]]'', [[Virgil]] stated that he had been nurtured by Parthenope, writing: {{quote|text=At that time sweet Parthenope was nurturing me, Virgil, as I flourished in the pursuits of my inglorious leisure...|sign=[[Virgil]]|source=[[Georgics]]<ref name="Miles" />{{rp|289}}}} In addition, Parthenope has served as the inspiration for a number of other works, such as [[Manuel de Zumaya]]'s ''[[Partenope (Zumaya)|Partenope]]'' and the [[ancient Greek novel]] ''[[Mētiokhos kai Parthenopē]]''.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Hägg |editor1-first=Thomas |editor2-last=Utas |editor2-first=Bo |date=2003 |title=The Virgin and Her Lover: Fragments of an Ancient Greek Novel and a Persian Epic Poem |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H2KiFE71wJIC&pg=PA49&dq=Parthenope+siren&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Lk6vU57oM9KOqgb904BQ&ved=0CBwQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |location=Leiden, Netherlands |publisher=[[Brill Publishers]] |page=5 |isbn=90-04-13260-0 |accessdate=30 June 2014 }}</ref> Also, several operas based on the myth of Parthenope were composed on the 18th century by [[Domenico Sarro|Sarro]] (1722), [[Leonardo Vinci|Vinci]] (1725), [[George Frideric Handel|Handel]] (1730), [[Antonio Vivaldi|Vivaldi]] (1738) and [[Johann Adolph Hasse|Hasse]] (1767).
